04060nam a22006375i 9780292799387DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20211991txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927993877 a10.7560/7112352doi  a(DE-B1597)588413  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPS153.M4bH47 1991eb 7aLIT0040502bisacsh04a817/.5409868722201 aHernandez, Guillermo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChicano Satire :bA Study in Literary Culture /cGuillermo Hernandez. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1991  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Satire: An Introduction -- t2. Luis Valdez and Actos of Teatro Campesino -- t3. José Montoya: From the RCAF to the Trio Casindio -- t4. Rolando Hinojosa: Klail City Death Trip Series -- t5. Conclusions -- tNotes -- tWorks Consulted -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGeographically close to Mexico, but surrounded by Anglo-American culture in the United States, Chicanos experience many cultural tensions and contradictions. Their lifeways are no longer identical with Mexican norms, nor are they fully assimilated to Anglo-American patterns. Coping with these tensions—knowing how much to let go of, how much to keep—is a common concern of Chicano writers, who frequently use satire as a means of testing norms and deviations from acceptable community standards. In this groundbreaking study, Guillermo Hernández focuses on the uses of satire in the works of three authors—Luis Valdez, Rolando Hinojosa, and José Montoya—and on the larger context of Chicano culture in which satire operates. Hernández looks specifically at the figures of the pocho (the assimilated Chicano) and the pachuco (the zoot-suiter, or urbanized youth). He shows how changes in their literary treatment—from simple ridicule to more understanding and respect—reflect the culture's changes in attitude toward the process of assimilation. Hernández also offers many important insights into the process of cultural definition that engaged Chicano writers during the 1960s and 1970s. He shows how the writers imaginatively and syncretically formed new norms for the Chicano experience, based on elements from both Mexican and United States culture but congruent with the historical reality of Chicanos. With its emphasis on culture change and creation, Chicano Satire will be of interest across a range of human sciences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aAmerican literaturexMexican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aMexican Americans in literature. 0aMexican AmericansxIntellectual life. 0aSatire, AmericanxMexican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / Hispanic American.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292799387423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292799387/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK